Important fact to preserve: `MutexRefreshCoordinator` failed under the concurrent test `auth_refresh_deduplicates_parallel_requests`.

That supports the concern that the mutex was scoped incorrectly, released too early, or not tied to the real contention key. If the current direction is an async queue, the important design point is that enqueueing must be the deduplication boundary:

```ts
const existing = refreshJobs.get(tenantId)
if (existing) return existing.promise

const job = queue.add(() => refreshTenantToken(tenantId))
refreshJobs.set(tenantId, job.promise)

job.promise.finally(() => {
  refreshJobs.delete(tenantId)
})

return job.promise
```

The queue should be keyed per tenant/token, and the “job exists” marker must be written synchronously before any `await`. Otherwise the queue can still accept duplicate refresh jobs from parallel requests.
